---
// Trust surfaces + the privacy dashboard. Pace does things on your Mac,
// so it has to be reversible, replayable, honest about failure, and honest
// about bytes. This section names the four surfaces that make an agent you
// can actually let touch your machine:
//
//   Undo banner       — every reversible mutation raises a 5s tap-to-undo
//   Reply replay       — 30s replay of the exact spoken text, no re-plan
//   Failure narration  — plain-language, deterministic, silenced on calls
//   Privacy dashboard  — reads the local audit log; "0 bytes" until proven otherwise
//
// Same shape as OnDevice: one claim, prose left, an artifact right. The
// artifact is a privacy-dashboard readout, because the headline number is
// the point. All claims verified against AGENTS.md / PROJECT_STATUS.md.
---

<section id="trust" class="px-6 py-24 md:py-36 border-t border-[var(--color-border-subtle)]">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-text-muted)] font-mono mb-6">
      Trust
    </p>

    <h2 class="pace-display text-4xl md:text-6xl text-white mb-12 max-w-3xl">
      An agent that touches your Mac <em>has to be reversible.</em>
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 md:gap-16 items-start">
      <div class="pace-prose">
        <p>
          Every change Pace can undo leaves a <strong>5-second undo
          banner</strong> next to the cursor — created a note, drafted a mail,
          added a reminder, edited a field. Tap it and the change rolls back.
          You don't have to remember what it did; the escape hatch shows up on
          its own.
        </p>
        <p>
          Missed the answer? A <strong>replay button</strong> sits under the
          panel for 30 seconds and speaks the exact same words back — it
          replays the audio, it doesn't re-run the planner, so you hear what
          you already heard, not a fresh guess.
        </p>
        <p>
          When something breaks — planner offline, a permission missing, a
          click that didn't land, the TTS sidecar down — Pace says so in
          <strong>plain language</strong>. That copy is written
          deterministically, not by a model, and it stays quiet when you're on
          a call.
        </p>
        <p>
          And the whole privacy claim is <strong>measured, not asserted.</strong>
          The in-app Privacy dashboard reads a local audit log and shows the
          exact bytes sent off your Mac, broken out by surface. It says zero
          until an off-device tier you turned on actually fires — then it says
          how much, and to whom.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mb-3 uppercase tracking-wider">
          Privacy dashboard — illustrative
        </p>
        <div
          class="font-mono text-sm bg-black border border-[var(--color-border-subtle)] rounded-lg p-5 leading-relaxed"
        >
          <div class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Pace › Privacy</div>
          <div class="mt-3 text-white/90">
            <span class="text-[var(--color-positive)] font-semibold text-base">0 bytes</span>
            sent off this Mac
          </div>
          <div class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">this session</div>
          <div class="mt-1">
            <span class="text-white/70">voice · screen · planner · tts </span>
            <span class="text-[var(--color-positive)]">local</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-white/70">meeting notes </span>
            <span class="text-[var(--color-positive)]">local (pinned)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-[var(--color-border-subtle)] text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
            turn on a cloud tier and this flips to
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-[var(--color-warning)]">14 KB → codex</span>
            <span class="text-white/60"> · capsule amber</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="pace-margin-note mt-5">
          The number is computed from the audit log,<br />
          not a promise on a marketing page.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
